# GDGFlashCard Project - Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
This is a Next.js 16 application with TypeScript, React 19, and Tailwind CSS v4 for building a flashcard system for GDG (Google Developer Groups).

## Tech Stack
- **Framework**: Next.js 16 (App Router)
- **Language**: TypeScript (strict mode)
- **UI Library**: React 19
- **Styling**: Tailwind CSS v4
- **UI Components**: shadcn/ui
- **Icons**: Lucide React
- **Utilities**: clsx, tailwind-merge, class-variance-authority

## shadcn/ui Setup & Usage

### Initialization
If shadcn/ui is not initialized in the project, use:
```bash
npx shadcn@latest init
```

### Adding Components
To install a specific shadcn/ui component (e.g., button):
```bash
npx shadcn@latest add button
```

### UI Component Guidelines
- **ALWAYS** use shadcn/ui components for all UI elements
- Before creating custom components, check if shadcn/ui has an equivalent
- Common components to use:
  - `button` - for all button elements
  - `card` - for card layouts
  - `input` - for form inputs
  - `label` - for form labels
  - `dialog` - for modals/dialogs
  - `dropdown-menu` - for dropdown menus
  - `toast` - for notifications
  - `form` - for forms with validation
  - `table` - for data tables
  - `tabs` - for tabbed interfaces
  - `badge` - for status indicators

## Code Style & Conventions

### TypeScript
- Use TypeScript for all files
- Prefer interfaces over types for object shapes
- Use proper type annotations, avoid `any`
- Leverage strict mode features
- Use type inference where appropriate

### React & Next.js
- Use React Server Components (RSC) by default
- Add `"use client"` directive only when necessary (hooks, event handlers, browser APIs)
- Use Next.js App Router conventions (`page.tsx`, `layout.tsx`, `loading.tsx`, `error.tsx`)
- Implement proper loading and error states
- Use Next.js Image component for images
- Use Next.js Link component for navigation

### File Structure
- Place React components in `src/components/`
- Place UI components (shadcn) in `src/components/ui/`
- Use path alias `@/` for imports (e.g., `@/components/ui/button`)
- Place app routes in `src/app/`
- Use kebab-case for file and folder names
- Use PascalCase for component names

### Component Structure
```tsx
// Server Component (default)
import { ComponentProps } from "@/types"

export default function MyComponent({ prop1, prop2 }: ComponentProps) {
  return (
    <div className="...">
      {/* JSX */}
    </div>
  )
}

// Client Component
"use client"

import { useState } from "react"
import { Button } from "@/components/ui/button"

export function MyClientComponent() {
  const [state, setState] = useState()
  
  return (
    <Button onClick={() => setState(...)}>
      Click me
    </Button>
  )
}
```

